    "baseball_pulse": "TRANSACTIONS\n\nSeveral roster moves with dynasty relevance emerged from opening weekend activity. The Giants designated Tyler Fitzgerald for assignment, acquired Dylan Smith from Detroit on a cash deal and optioned him to Triple-A, and traded Luis Matos to Milwaukee for cash considerations. The Marlins activated shortstop Leo Jimenez after acquiring him from Toronto and optioned infielder Deyvison De Los Santos to Triple-A, positioning Connor Norby for increased at-bats at first base while Christopher Morel recovers. The Blue Jays signed Austin Voth to a minor league deal and the Twins signed John Brebbia to a minor league contract. Shaun Anderson was selected to the majors by the Angels after a minor league deal. The Royals are considering a temporary role change for Carlos Estevez, who remains in a walking boot and is unlikely to be available Monday. Andrew Kittredge will begin a rehab assignment Wednesday for Baltimore. Nick Lodolo is set to make a rehab start Thursday for Cincinnati as he works back from a finger injury.\n\nPROSPECTS\n\nSpencer Jones continues to impress at Triple-A for the Yankees, launching a 109.1 mph homer in his first game of the season and recording five batted balls at 104.1 mph or faster, showcasing elite power production. Carlos Lagrange, the Yankees' top pitching prospect, threw the fastest pitch recorded during minor league opening weekend at 101.3 mph during his Triple-A debut, though the organization made the difficult decision to send him down from spring training. James Tibbs III is on a heater for the Dodgers' Triple-A affiliate with a two-homer game, posting a 2.105 OPS with elite batted ball data suggesting a potential breakout. The Brewers' all-rookie battery of Brandon Sproat and Jeferson Quero made history on Sunday as the first such pairing since 2018, with both prospects earning praise from the organization. Justin Crawford, the Phillies' number three prospect, demonstrated his ability at Citizens Bank Park by conquering one of the trickiest outfields in baseball on his first try.\n\nVIBES\n\nOpening weekend showcased several compelling storylines heading into the season. Five teams remain undefeated after three games: the Dodgers, Yankees, Blue Jays, Marlins, and Brewers. Joey Wiemer made history for the Nationals by becoming the third player since 1961 to reach safely in his first eight plate appearances with a new team. Christian Yelich delivered a pinch-hit three-run homer to cap a six-run inning and secure a series sweep for Milwaukee. Brendan Donovan contributed a three-run homer to"
